05937nam a22007455i 9781782387855DE-B159720221004111318.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221004t20042004nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97817823878557 a10.1515/97817823878552doi  a(DE-B1597)636248  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHD4875.G4 7aHIS0271002bisacsh04a331.11a331.11/73222200aWorking for the Enemy :bFord, General Motors, and Forced Labor in Germany during the Second World War /ced. by Reinhold Billstein, Karola Fings, Anita Kugler, Nicholas Levis. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2004] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tLIST OF ILLUSTRATIONS -- tLIST OF ABBREVIATIONS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tPART ONE -- tPROLOGUE The Pre-War Years -- tCHAPTER 1 AIRPLANES FOR THE FÜHRER -- tCHAPTER 2 1945. HOW THE AMERICANS TOOK OVER COLOGNE—AND DISCOVERED FORD WERKE’S ROLE IN THE WAR -- tCHAPTER 3 WALTER RIETIG AND THE EFFORT OF REMEMBRANCE -- tPART TWO -- tCHAPTER 4 FORCED LABOR AT FORD WERKE IN COLOGNE -- tCHAPTER 5 “AND THEY TOOK THE 38 OF US TO FORD” -- tCHAPTER 6 MEMORY AND LIABILITY -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tNOTES -- tAppendix: Organization of the Forced Labor System at War Operations -- tGLOSSARY -- tSELECT BIBLIOGRAPHY -- tILLUSTRATION SOURCES -- tTHE AUTHORS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGeneral Motors, the largest corporation on earth today, has been the owner since 1929 of Adam Opel AG, Russelsheim, the maker of Opel cars. Ford Motor Company in 1931 built the Ford Werke factory in Cologne, now the headquarters of European Ford. In this book, historians tell the astonishing story of what happened at Opel and Ford Werke under the Third Reich, and of the aftermath today. Long before the Second World War, key American executives at Ford and General Motors were eager to do business with Nazi Germany. Ford Werke and Opel became indispensable suppliers to the German armed forces, together providing most of the trucks that later motorized the Nazi attempt to conquer Europe. After the outbreak of war in 1939, Opel converted its largest factory to warplane parts production, and both companies set up extensive maintenance and repair networks to help keep the war machine on wheels. During the war, the Nazi Reich used millions of POWs, civilians from German-occupied countries, and concentration camp prisoners as forced laborers in the German homefront economy. Starting in 1940, Ford Werke and Opel also made use of thousands of forced laborers. POWs and civilian detainees, deported to Germany by the Nazi authorities, were kept at private camps owned and managed by the companies. In the longest section of the book, ten people who were forced to work at Ford Werke recall their experiences in oral testimonies. For more than fifty years, legal and political obstacles frustrated efforts to gain compensation for Nazi-era forced labor; in the most recent case, a $12 billion lawsuit was filed against the computer giant I.B.M. by a group of Gypsy organizations. In 1998, former forced laborers filed dozens of class action lawsuits against German corporations in U.S. courts. The concluding chapter reviews the subsequent, immensely complex negotiations towards a settlement - which involved Germany, the United States, Poland, Russia, Ukraine, Belarus, Czech Republic, Israel and several other countries, as well as dozens of well-known German corporations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aAutomobile industry and tradexMilitary aspectszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aForced laborzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xConscript laborzGermany. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xPrison